bit in Bud Tribble's keynote

00:03:39.900 --> 00:03:42.780
presentation yesterday,
but Apple's really striving to

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:45.060
bring innovation to the data center.

00:03:45.060 --> 00:03:49.000
We think that there's a lot of
innovative new technologies,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.030
simplifications that we can
bring back to the data center.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:57.780
So what we're doing is, as we mentioned,
we're building this industrial-strength

00:03:57.780 --> 00:03:59.500
server operating system.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.660
We are leveraging the capabilities
of the open-source groups.

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:07.220
We're building upon the projects
that they've provided for us.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:12.010
And we're also focusing on standards,
and standards, as you know, is very key,

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:16.200
because it doesn't lock you as a
customer into one particular vendor.

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:20.700
It allows you to pick the best
solution for what you're deploying.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.130
We're also trying to build a product that
has a lot of different services built in.

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:29.800
We want this product to be very flexible,
fit into different environments.

00:04:29.800 --> 00:04:32.250
So there's a lot of different
services in the product,

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:35.110
everything from file and print
services and internet and web,

00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:37.870
desktop management technologies,
media streaming.

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:40.220
There's a whole wealth of
services that are built in.

00:04:42.250 --> 00:04:45.980
But again, our goal here is to really
lower the cost of ownership.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:48.900
Lower the cost of
ownership for our servers,

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:53.110
but also for our desktop systems with
our desktop management technologies

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:55.210
that we've built into the product.

00:04:56.010 --> 00:04:57.060
So what's new in Panther?

00:04:57.250 --> 00:04:59.780
Well, there's a wonderful
array of new features,

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:01.360
and this is just some of them.

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:05.440
We've got a really new,
improved Darwin core operating system,

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:07.740
the BSD layer of the operating system.

00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:09.440
As you'll find in some
of the presentations,

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:11.510
there's a lot of new enhancements there.

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:14.220
We've got a new automatic
server setup feature,

00:05:14.230 --> 00:05:17.430
making it very easy to configure
an entire rack of X Servers

00:05:17.800 --> 00:05:21.360
or just a single server,
all from a configuration file.

00:05:21.390 --> 00:05:25.400
We'll be talking about that more later
today in some of the other sessions.

00:05:26.190 --> 00:05:27.450
We've listened to your feedback.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:29.900
We've improved our
administration software,

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:31.930
have a new server admin application.

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:34.040
We've built in Samba 3.

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:38.200
Apple's Mac OS X Server is really
going to be the first commercial

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:40.500
operating system to ship with Samba 3.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:43.300
And Samba 3 gives us
a lot of new features,

00:05:43.300 --> 00:05:47.820
the ability to support PDCs so we
can host Windows Home directories,

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:51.080
have a single account for
a login and authentication.

00:05:53.710 --> 00:05:54.510
Open Directory.

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:56.360
We have a new version of Open Directory.

00:05:56.360 --> 00:06:00.670
Again,
not only LDAP-based directory services,

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:02.400
but also Kerberos for authentication.

00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:06.180
Single Sign-On goes along with Kerberos,
so the user only has to

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:08.660
enter a single password,
and they can access other

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:09.810
services on their network.

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:14.610
A complete end-to-end VPN solution.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:18.450
We have a VPN client in the
desktop operating system and now

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:20.540
a VPN server in Mac OS X Server.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:26.260
JBoss application servers for
hosting J2EE-based applications.

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:28.940
And then also the new
Postfix mail server,

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:33.730
having a really industrial-strength
mail server finally on our server.

