00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:57.270
So now we're going to take a tour through
some of the features in Panther Server,

00:06:57.270 --> 00:06:59.530
and specifically we're going
to focus on some of the things

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:01.590
that are new in this release,
but we'll cover all of it,

00:07:01.610 --> 00:07:03.420
as Eric mentioned,
for those of you who maybe are

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:04.850
not so familiar with the product.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:09.430
And as many of you heard yesterday,
underlying Mac OS X Server is

00:07:09.430 --> 00:07:11.030
a Unix foundation.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:15.050
It's based on open source, based on BSD,
and it provides the scalability

00:07:15.050 --> 00:07:18.820
and the reliability you need for
a competitive server platform.

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:22.140
We've upgraded this to
BSD 5 in Panther Server,

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:24.920
and with this we get
a lot of improvements.

00:07:24.920 --> 00:07:28.280
One of them is we've improved
performance in this release.

00:07:28.280 --> 00:07:30.690
We've improved the raw throughput,
and in addition,

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:32.520
we've added POSIX asynchronous I.O.

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:36.340
support, which has been a popular request
from our database developers.

00:07:36.340 --> 00:07:39.700
We've also enhanced the
scalability of the file system.

00:07:39.700 --> 00:07:42.500
We now support up to 16
terabyte file systems.

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:46.270
Journaling is something that
was introduced for the server

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:48.860
in HFS in an update for 10.2.

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:53.080
And we've now integrated that into HFS,
and it is the default

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:56.260
for all HFS in Mac OS X,
journaling file system.

00:07:56.260 --> 00:08:01.420
And finally, another popular request,
case sensitive HFS Plus for people that

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:07.920
are sharing file systems out to Unix
clients using XSERVs as NFS servers.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:10.450
Case sensitivity has been
a very popular request,

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:13.080
so you now have that as
an option in the server.

00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:20.890
With BSD networking also comes
advanced features like IPv6 and IPsec,

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:26.130
as well as multi-homing for
hosting multiple web domains.

00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:31.240
For capable Ethernet interfaces,
we support Gigabit JumboFrame support.

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:34.410
And we also have IP over Firewire,
which makes a great back-channel

00:08:34.410 --> 00:08:37.730
networking interface for IP failover.

00:08:39.300 --> 00:08:41.800
IP Failover provides high
availability in the server.

00:08:41.800 --> 00:08:44.500
It allows you to set up a pair
of servers that are clustered

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:45.690
and can support failover.

00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:49.330
Each one can monitor the other and
pick up its IP addresses and its

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.710
services in case the other one fails
and then relinquish them when the

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:54.660
second server comes back online.

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:58.620
We also support automatic restart,
which allows any service to

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:00.450
be restarted should it fail.

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:04.880
It also will restart the whole
system in the event of a system hang.

00:09:05.830 --> 00:09:08.120
And finally,
software RAID provides reliability

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:10.800
and performance in the storage layer.

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:13.210
And of course,
there's hardware RAID as well

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:15.290
from the XSERV RAID product line.

00:09:16.810 --> 00:09:18.460
And for anybody that's
familiar with Unix,

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:22.390
of course, with BSD comes all the
familiar networking and

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:26.770
system administration tools,
secure login through SSH,

00:09:26.770 --> 00:09:29.550
a variety of shells,
all the BSD commands.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:33.110
It's very familiar to anybody that's
administered a BSD or a Linux server,

00:09:33.110 --> 00:09:34.710
so you'll feel right at home.

00:09:37.540 --> 00:09:40.900
Now we could stop there and just
take all the open source foundation

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:43.420
and throw the services on it,
but we didn't.

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:47.280
And we've put a lot of effort into making
sure that it's all integrated and making

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:51.370
sure that the management tools that
we provide make the whole system very

00:09:51.370 --> 00:09:53.220
easy to set up and very easy to use.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:56.530
And so what we've done is we've
added tools for automatic setup,

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:58.100
automatic configuration.

00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:01.420
We've provided a wide suite
of server management tools for

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:05.020
ongoing day-to-day management,
and we've provided directory

00:10:05.020 --> 00:10:07.090
management tools for the directory.

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:12.600
Automatic server setup allows you to take
a server right out of the box and set it

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:14.460
up very simply in a matter of seconds.

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:18.300
You can take a server configuration
for things like IP address,

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:21.890
domain names, service setup,
and you can save that into a

00:10:21.890 --> 00:10:25.670
file and put it on a portable
device like a FireWire drive,

00:10:25.860 --> 00:10:28.330
an iPod, or a USB keychain drive.

00:10:28.340 --> 00:10:31.390
And then when you take a
server right out of the box,

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:34.510
brand new, turn it on,
plug it in to the network,

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:36.460
you can just plug that
drive into the server.

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.410
It will recognize the configuration
file and configure itself

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:42.860
automatically in a matter of seconds.

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:46.060
Now, that works great if you have
one or two or three servers,

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.940
but if you have a whole rack of servers,
even just moving the drive around

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:50.220
can get kind of cumbersome.

00:10:50.220 --> 00:10:52.900
So what we've also done
is allow you to store this

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:55.090
configuration out on the network.

00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:57.950
So you can take a rack of
servers that are brand new,

00:10:58.030 --> 00:11:02.390
never been touched,
plug them into the network,

00:11:02.420 --> 00:11:04.320
turn them all on,
and have them all grab their

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:07.300
configuration directly and be up
and running in a matter of seconds.

00:11:07.300 --> 00:11:09.300
So you can't get much simpler than that.

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:14.340
So let's move over to a quick demo here,
and we'll have Eric come up and

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:17.660
