00:15:11.780 --> 00:15:14.080
Lastly,
Workgroup Manager allows you to manage

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:15.740
the directory in Mac OS X Server.

00:15:15.740 --> 00:15:19.140
All of Mac OS X Server is
based on directory system,

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:21.380
open directory that underlies it.

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:23.570
And all of the information
about accounts,

00:15:23.600 --> 00:15:26.580
authentication, service configuration is
stored in the directory.

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:29.340
And Workgroup Manager lets
you easily manage accounts,

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:31.620
account settings,
as well as preferences and

00:15:31.630 --> 00:15:34.840
other things that can be
configured through the directory.

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:36.630
Eric Zelenkka, Greg Burns,
Francois Jouaux

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:39.400
Because Mac OS X Server is based on LDAP,
this actually works

00:15:39.400 --> 00:15:42.820
with any LDAP v3 server,
the one that comes with Mac OS X Server,

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.960
as well as if you're using a third-party
LDAP server for your environment,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.430
it'll work with those as well.

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:51.810
Another new feature we've added for
Panther Server is a directory inspector,

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.530
which is a very cool feature for
power users that actually allows

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:59.380
you to go in and edit the raw
records in the directory server.

00:15:59.380 --> 00:16:01.570
So it's not something you
need on an everyday basis,

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:04.050
but it's a powerful feature
for people that need it.

00:16:07.230 --> 00:16:10.250
So open directory is an area
that we've made a lot of

00:16:10.250 --> 00:16:12.120
improvements in Panther Server.

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:15.740
Open directory is Mac OS X's
framework for accessing directory

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:17.580
and authentication information.

00:16:17.660 --> 00:16:21.940
All of the services in the client
and the server use open directory.

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:26.910
And open directory allows us
to integrate with the native

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:31.100
services in Mac OS X Server,
LDAP and Kerberos,

00:16:31.180 --> 00:16:35.100
as well as a variety of other services,
NIS for Unix environments,

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:39.810
Active Directory, NetInfo, BSD files.

00:16:40.130 --> 00:16:43.820
So you have a wide variety of
choices for configuration and for

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:48.500
storing directory and authentication
information for your Mac OS X systems.

00:16:49.480 --> 00:16:54.120
So in Mac OS X Server,
we provide the services themselves.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:59.180
LDAP is now based on OpenLDAP,
and Kerberos is based on MIT's Kerberos.

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:01.860
And Kerberos provides
us with single sign-on,

00:17:01.940 --> 00:17:04.520
which is new to
Panther and Panther Server.

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:09.400
This allows you to log in once securely
at login time at the login window,

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:12.590
and then access all of your services
with a secure Kerberos ticket.

00:17:12.600 --> 00:17:16.020
So file services, email,
you don't have to store passwords

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:18.150
separately for each service now.

00:17:18.790 --> 00:17:21.620
And also, for those of you that are
familiar with Mac OS X Server,

00:17:21.620 --> 00:17:23.800
this also gives us
authenticated automounts.

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:27.720
So this is another important security
improvement in Mac OS X Server.

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:31.720
We know that not all of the
services are going to be Kerberized,

00:17:31.730 --> 00:17:35.450
that some of you will always need
to access legacy services that

00:17:35.450 --> 00:17:37.580
use standard password encryption.

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:42.380
And so for that, we have Password Server,
which provides legacy encryption methods.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:48.300
So Single Server,
Single Sidon is based on Kerberos.

00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:51.280
We are adopting MIT Kerberos for this.

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:52.970
It's based on V5.

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:56.480
We're not changing the
Kerberos protocol in any way.

00:17:56.600 --> 00:18:00.760
And so because of that,
our implementation, our server,

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:05.620
our client can be used with
any deployment of MIT Kerberos.

00:18:05.740 --> 00:18:11.090
So whether you choose to use Mac OS X as
your KDC or whether you choose to use

00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:15.420
your own residing on another platform,
our services will work.

00:18:15.430 --> 00:18:19.380
Now, of course,
we provide KDC and Mac OS X Server to

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:23.280
make it really simple out of the box to
set up and configure and have a complete

00:18:23.350 --> 00:18:26.230
authentication and directory environment.

00:18:31.580 --> 00:18:34.000
Another improvement we've made in
Open Directory is to improve the

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:35.760
scalability of the directory services.

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:39.520
LDAP is now hosted on
Berkeley DB for scalability.

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:41.900
For those of you
familiar with the server,

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:44.640
in the past it was hosted
on a NetInfo backend.

00:18:44.640 --> 00:18:48.260
We still have NetInfo in the system
for those of you that want to use

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:52.380
it for legacy support reasons,
but for Mac OS X Server, Panther Server,

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:56.260
and beyond, all of the default directory
services are based on LDAP,

00:18:56.300 --> 00:18:58.180
on Open LDAP on Berkeley DB.

00:18:58.840 --> 00:19:01.540
This gives us the capability
of hot backup for greater

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:05.870
availability and scalability to
over 100,000 records per server.

00:19:05.870 --> 00:19:09.480
Of course, if you need more than that,
you can also replicate your services.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:14.030
We provide replication locally that
allows you to have greater availability

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:18.080
or to have multiple servers serving
the same directory information,

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:22.460
and you can also replicate remotely for
greater availability for remote sites.

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:25.100
And another thing we've done, again,
to further improve the overall

00:19:25.220 --> 00:19:26.180
usability of the system out of the box,
is to have a more secure system.

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:30.750
The overall usability of the system
out of the box is we've integrated

00:19:30.750 --> 00:19:34.830
the Kerberos KDC backend with password
server and with the LDAP server so

00:19:34.900 --> 00:19:39.110
that all the replication happens simply
and automatically out of the box.

00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:40.820
You don't have to worry
about wiring this up.

00:19:40.930 --> 00:19:42.740
It's all connected and integrated fully.

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:45.190
And so with that,
we'll bring up Eric just to

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:48.390
show you how simple it is to
set up Open Directory services

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:49.700
in Panther Server.

