Thanks, Eric.

00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:02.480
Let's go back to presentation.

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:05.540
So that's open directory two.

00:21:08.340 --> 00:21:10.700
So one of the most popular
services for any server,

00:21:10.700 --> 00:21:14.200
obviously, is workgroup services,
file and print for the local intranet.

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:17.120
And of course,
we provide a wide variety of services

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:18.480
there for both file and print.

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:21.800
Looking specifically at
the file sharing side,

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:24.880
we provide native
services for Mac clients,

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:28.690
AFP, SMB Sys for Windows clients,
and NFS for Unix.

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:31.230
We've improved the
performance in this release.

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:34.020
As before,
we provide support for multiple

00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:37.630
protocols on any SharePoint so all
clients can share the same data.

00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:41.510
All the authentication is unified
through the LDAP backend with

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:42.600
the same account information.

00:21:42.650 --> 00:21:47.060
And we have disk quota support so you
can control the use of server resources.

00:21:49.080 --> 00:21:52.390
We made some improvements
to NFS in this release.

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:58.940
One popular use of NFS in the server
is to reshare the NFS volumes via AFP.

00:21:59.100 --> 00:22:04.030
NFS has some security compromises
when you use that as a sharing method.

00:22:04.050 --> 00:22:07.890
And so a lot of people like
to take a bank of X Serves and

00:22:07.890 --> 00:22:11.570
use them to reshare enterprise
storage via AFP to their clients.

00:22:11.670 --> 00:22:16.580
And another area we've improved NFS is

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:19.380
Greater performance and also
improving the reliability in

00:22:19.380 --> 00:22:23.100
this release and adding NFS file
locking support for data integrity.

00:22:25.830 --> 00:22:30.710
We've added Samba 3 for Windows client
support and integrated PDC or

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:33.820
primary domain controller
support directly into the server.

00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:37.400
So that's all configured directly
out of the box very simply and easily

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:39.910
through the administration tools.

00:22:39.940 --> 00:22:43.480
And what this means is now that
when you log into a Windows client

00:22:43.480 --> 00:22:47.830
at the Windows login window,
you can use the same authentication

00:22:47.830 --> 00:22:52.540
data from Mac OS X Server that's
hosted in LDAP that your Mac clients

00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:54.190
use or that any other client uses.

00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:56.900
You can share a home directory
with your Mac client,

00:22:57.140 --> 00:23:00.080
whether you're accessing
it from Windows or Mac,

00:23:00.160 --> 00:23:03.000
and you can host your roaming
profiles on the server.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.710
That's all built into the system,
and it's configured through the GUI.

00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:11.000
And finally,
we've added Active Directory integration.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:16.100
This is native integration that's new
to Panther for both client and server.

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:19.200
And what this means is that there
are no schema changes required in

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:22.370
Active Directory to support Mac OS X.

00:23:25.180 --> 00:23:28.350
It integrates with the Kerberos
authentication and Active Directory.

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:31.080
And for large installations
that have multiple domains in

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:33.280
their Active Directory forest,
we support automatic

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:34.520
multi-domain authentication.

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:38.250
So it's all very simple to use,
very simple to configure out of the box.

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:41.790
And all of the services
in Mac OS X Server can use

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:46.550
Active Directory for storage
of their directory accounts.

00:23:49.490 --> 00:23:51.900
Another area that's important
in workgroup services

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:53.660
is workgroup management.

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:56.520
We spend a lot of effort at
Apple making Mac OS X very

00:23:56.710 --> 00:23:59.910
simple and easy to configure,
easy to set up and use.

00:23:59.960 --> 00:24:02.230
And that's great if you have one system.

00:24:02.230 --> 00:24:04.300
But, you know,
you might have more than one.

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:07.220
You might have, you know, a hundred,
a thousand.

00:24:07.220 --> 00:24:08.890
And then, you know, what do you do then?

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:12.330
Well, we have a set of products
in Mac OS X Server that make

00:24:12.390 --> 00:24:14.060
this very easy to manage.

00:24:14.060 --> 00:24:18.870
You can install systems on a large
number of desktops on the network.

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.020
You can set them up.

00:24:20.020 --> 00:24:23.380
You can configure them and manage
them on a day-to-day basis.

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:27.100
These are workgroup management
services in Mac OS X Server.

00:24:27.100 --> 00:24:30.890
It's all directory-based,
so all of this system configuration

00:24:30.890 --> 00:24:32.670
is stored in the directory.

00:24:32.690 --> 00:24:36.820
We provide services that allow
you to control preferences,

00:24:36.930 --> 00:24:40.910
to set preferences on these systems,
to control their use of resources

00:24:41.010 --> 00:24:43.330
both on the system and on the network.

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:48.400
And we provide tools to allow network
installation and setup of these systems.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:51.530
Something that's new in
Panther Server also is the ability

00:24:51.650 --> 00:24:53.400
to do this on mobile systems.

00:24:53.540 --> 00:24:56.190
So if you have mobile computers,
Power Books, iBooks,

00:24:56.190 --> 00:24:58.080
you can manage their accounts.

00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:00.750
You can manage the
authentication information,

00:25:00.810 --> 00:25:04.010
the account information,
and all of the preferences and everything

00:25:04.010 --> 00:25:05.200
else that you set through the directory.

00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:07.640
And that will be synchronized
automatically when your

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:09.190
system comes onto the network.

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:14.190
And so even mobile computers now
can be managed using these tools.

00:25:19.010 --> 00:25:24.920
And finally, two tools for installing and
managing images on the network,

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:25.960
NetBoot and NetInstall.

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:28.360
NetBoot obviously allows
you to boot a system,

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:30.550
a desktop, or a server over the network.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:34.720
And two things that we've added in
Panther Server are the ability to

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:38.950
NetBoot over HTTP as well as NFS,
and also the ability to do

00:25:38.950 --> 00:25:42.310
a fully diskless NetBoot,
which is very handy if you have an

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:46.540
image of network diagnostic tools
where you want to debug a problem.

00:25:46.540 --> 00:25:51.250
You can NetBoot completely
independently of any disk that's running

00:25:51.370 --> 00:25:53.040
remotely or locally on the desktop.

00:25:55.350 --> 00:25:58.000
For network install,
this allows you to install systems

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.140
over the network using Netboot.

00:26:00.140 --> 00:26:02.340
And you can use it to
distribute software images,

00:26:02.430 --> 00:26:04.020
distribute software updates.

00:26:04.020 --> 00:26:07.300
And we've made a couple improvements
to this in Panther Server.

00:26:07.300 --> 00:26:10.350
One is we've redesigned the tool
that you use to create the images,

00:26:10.470 --> 00:26:13.010
the network image utility,
to make it simpler to use and

00:26:13.030 --> 00:26:15.980
add a lot more options to it,
more powerful.

00:26:15.980 --> 00:26:18.670
And another option that we've added--
it's been a big request-- is the

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:20.420
ability to do full image installs.

00:26:20.590 --> 00:26:23.940
So now you can take a volume
that hosts system software,

00:26:23.950 --> 00:26:26.680
has applications installed,
it's fully configured,

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:30.980
and you can clone that and do network
installs of system or volume images,

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:35.290
as well as packages or
clean system installs.

00:26:38.780 --> 00:26:43.290
So that covers the workgroup
services built into Mac OS X Server.

