You can send extremely high
bitrate content over your

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:38.940
network using multicast.

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:43.720
It supports MPEG-4,
all the QuickTime content, MP3.

00:27:43.720 --> 00:27:47.980
It's compatible with
Windows and Macintosh players.

00:27:48.860 --> 00:27:51.620
It's also a server that is
powerful enough to be used for

00:27:51.620 --> 00:27:53.400
streaming across the internet.

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:56.040
So a lot of the big content
distribution networks that you see,

00:27:56.040 --> 00:27:59.520
including the ones that Apple uses,
are using QuickTime streaming

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:05.080
server as their streaming server for
serving MPEG-4 and QuickTime content.

00:28:05.080 --> 00:28:09.270
And then with the advent of
802.11 and a PowerBook in the

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:13.020
QuickTime broadcaster application,
you can actually have a

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:15.110
completely mobile solution.

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:17.430
So you can actually take
a PowerBook wirelessly,

00:28:17.430 --> 00:28:18.560
walk around the room.

00:28:18.860 --> 00:28:22.850
Stream broadcast, send it up to a server,
and stream that out over the internet.

00:28:22.850 --> 00:28:24.110
We've seen that done quite a few times.

00:28:26.270 --> 00:28:32.040
So new with Panther Server is
QuickTime Streaming Server 5.

00:28:32.140 --> 00:28:34.640
It's got all the same
features that it's always had.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:36.200
It has no license fees.

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:38.520
We don't charge per stream.

00:28:38.670 --> 00:28:40.920
Supports Mac, Windows, and Linux clients.

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:44.680
It supports Linux clients
through its MPEG-4 compatibility.

00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:48.900
And it supports Instant On technology,
which basically eliminates all of

00:28:48.900 --> 00:28:52.070
the buffering messages you would
see normally when you're streaming.

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:55.580
It starts up as fast as if it's playing
locally on a good broadband connection.

00:28:55.640 --> 00:28:57.990
Skip protection,
which is our technology for guaranteeing

00:28:58.110 --> 00:29:00.050
quality of service across the internet.

00:29:00.190 --> 00:29:02.140
As we know,
there are always blips in the internet.

00:29:02.210 --> 00:29:06.350
Skip protection is the technology
that basically eliminates those

00:29:06.350 --> 00:29:07.960
blips when you're watching content.

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.800
And the servers perform extremely well.

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:16.080
They can, off of a single machine,
stream up to 4,000 concurrent streams.

00:29:16.260 --> 00:29:19.080
And if you want to do more than that,
it's really just a matter of

00:29:19.130 --> 00:29:20.590
buying a few more experts.

00:29:21.440 --> 00:29:24.310
Also new with Panther Server is
QTSS Publisher.

00:29:24.310 --> 00:29:28.300
So this is a new application
that provides a way to remotely

00:29:28.300 --> 00:29:33.580
manage your QuickTime content.

00:29:33.870 --> 00:29:34.690
For putting up on the internet.

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:37.060
So it automatically takes
care of things like hinting or

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:39.950
preparing it for the web servers.

00:29:39.950 --> 00:29:42.120
It'll automatically create web galleries.

00:29:42.120 --> 00:29:46.320
It's tightly integrated with the
Apache web server on Mac OS X Server.

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:48.580
It has all of the UI for
creating playlists,

00:29:48.580 --> 00:29:51.700
managing the order of playlists,
scheduling playlists,

00:29:51.800 --> 00:29:52.680
and doing all of those things.

00:29:52.720 --> 00:29:56.540
MP3 playlists as well as
QuickTime content playlists.

00:29:56.540 --> 00:29:59.320
It allows you to edit annotations.

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:03.140
And behind the scenes,
all of this is happening with some Unix

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:05.340
tools that we wrote for Panther Server.

00:30:05.340 --> 00:30:08.020
So you can now, from the command line,
do things like hint movies,

00:30:08.020 --> 00:30:09.960
change annotations,
all of that from the shell,

00:30:10.070 --> 00:30:11.900
if that's the way you'd
like to do things.

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:19.400
QuickTime Broadcaster is a product
we shipped about a year ago.

00:30:19.420 --> 00:30:22.420
It allows you to take
any FireWire camera,

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:24.980
plug it in,
and do a broadcast from your computer.

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:27.680
It supports all of the QuickTime codecs,
and of course,

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:29.160
it supports the standard MPEG-4.

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:32.990
It's got a...

00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:34.960
A bit of functionality we
call reliable transport.

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:38.800
And what that is,
is a guarantee that the stream

00:30:38.800 --> 00:30:42.920
from the broadcaster to the server
is going to be a solid stream.

00:30:42.920 --> 00:30:45.490
And that's really important,
because if you lose packets between

00:30:45.490 --> 00:30:48.330
the broadcaster and the server,
every single client sees that loss.

00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:50.340
So we've got a way to guarantee
that all the packets get there.

00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:54.180
It supports unicast
and multicast as well.

00:30:54.180 --> 00:30:57.680
And it delivers ISO-compliant streams.

00:30:57.680 --> 00:31:00.220
So those are MPEG-4 streams
to any standard player.

00:31:00.350 --> 00:31:03.130
So it'll play on Linux for
any player that supports the

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:04.990
standard ISO MPEG-4 player.

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:10.200
So networking services.

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:14.620
Got both some old stuff and
some new stuff in Panther.

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:16.750
I shouldn't say old,
I mean it was available

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:17.720
in Jaguar's server.

00:31:17.720 --> 00:31:19.210
I'm going to go through both of those.

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:21.080
We have an entire slew
of networking services.

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:23.220
I'm not going to go through all of these.

00:31:24.240 --> 00:31:27.850
DNS, DHCP,
we've got a network time server,

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:28.960
firewall.

00:31:29.010 --> 00:31:32.660
We've added VPN, which is new,
authentication.

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:34.150
And it's all standard.

00:31:34.150 --> 00:31:38.130
So you can connect Macintoshes,
you can connect Windows machines,

00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:39.340
Linux machines.

00:31:39.340 --> 00:31:40.380
It's all completely standard.

00:31:40.380 --> 00:31:43.230
We don't believe in proprietary
technologies where we can help it.

00:31:44.600 --> 00:31:46.280
So, dynamic host configuration.

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:48.200
We've had DHCP in Jaguar's server.

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:51.070
We've added a couple of
things to the Panther server.

00:31:51.070 --> 00:31:55.720
DHCP, as you know, provides automatic
doling out of addresses.

00:31:55.800 --> 00:32:00.420
We've added the ability to specify
LDAP directories for those machines.

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:04.830
We've also added the ability in the
UI to bind a specific Ethernet address

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:07.060
to the IP address of any machine.

00:32:07.060 --> 00:32:10.120
So, you've got machines that want
to have a permanent IP address

00:32:10.120 --> 00:32:11.640
but have it served up via DHCP.

00:32:11.640 --> 00:32:14.240
You can do that now through
our admin application.

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:17.490
And, of course,
you can control IP address ranges,

00:32:17.490 --> 00:32:21.040
the lease times, and network routing,
things like that.

00:32:22.310 --> 00:32:24.640
Next, some networking,
network routing technologies.

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:28.740
So we've had NAT on the
desktop for Mac OS X Server.

00:32:28.740 --> 00:32:30.780
We've now moved that
functionality into the server.

00:32:30.780 --> 00:32:33.460
So in the server admin,
you can now configure NAT.

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:38.690
We've also added a VPN server,
and that's all configurable in

00:32:38.790 --> 00:32:41.520
the new server admin as well.

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:43.670
It works with all standards.

00:32:43.670 --> 00:32:48.550
It also works with Windows technologies
so that you can use things like

00:32:48.550 --> 00:32:51.240
MS-CHAP and PPTP as well as L2TP.

00:32:53.670 --> 00:32:54.870
So DNS.

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:59.930
So we've bumped the
version of Bind up to nine.

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:01.950
So good, like that.

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:07.110
So you're going to get dynamic DNS,
things like that.

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:09.880
And as everyone knows,
it's the most widely deployed

00:33:10.100 --> 00:33:12.240
DNS server on the internet.

00:33:12.390 --> 00:33:15.860
For those of you who really
like to configure Bind files,

00:33:15.890 --> 00:33:20.670
your job security is kind of limited now,
because we've added UI to the admin.

00:33:24.100 --> 00:33:26.980
And if you get a chance to look at it,
it's actually pretty slick.

00:33:27.030 --> 00:33:29.110
I think we did a good job
on the UI on this one.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:32.100
And Firewall.

00:33:32.100 --> 00:33:34.680
This isn't new,
but we have redone the UI on this.

00:33:34.680 --> 00:33:37.760
It's really simple to set
up kind of basic rules.

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:39.700
It's using the standard Berkeley IPFW.

00:33:39.700 --> 00:33:44.280
We also have some UI that will allow
the more advanced people to set up

00:33:44.280 --> 00:33:47.320
basically any rule that IPFW can handle.

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:51.730
Something we didn't have in the past,
all of the configuration for Firewall was

00:33:51.730 --> 00:33:54.260
actually stored up in a NetInfo database.

00:33:54.260 --> 00:33:56.130
We've moved that down into a config file.

00:33:56.130 --> 00:33:59.780
Although you can do everything in the UI,
if you need to SSH into a machine,

00:33:59.780 --> 00:34:02.830
if you're on a non-Macintosh machine,
you can always get in there and

00:34:02.930 --> 00:34:04.600
change those configurations that way.

00:34:04.600 --> 00:34:07.890
And next is mail services.

00:34:12.220 --> 00:34:14.240
So Mac OS X Server.

00:34:14.380 --> 00:34:18.370
Prior to Panther,
we had a proprietary mail server.

00:34:18.910 --> 00:34:20.960
It was a standard server.

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:22.740
It supported all of the
normal internet standards.

00:34:22.740 --> 00:34:26.620
We also had a web mail
server through Squirrel Mail.

00:34:26.620 --> 00:34:30.740
It allows connectivity because
it's all standard to any platform

00:34:30.740 --> 00:34:32.840
that supports standard mail.

00:34:32.840 --> 00:34:34.540
We've made a couple of changes.

00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:37.950
We no longer have a
proprietary mail server.

00:34:37.950 --> 00:34:40.760
We've moved to Postfix for the MTA.

00:34:43.200 --> 00:34:46.250
And we did that for a lot of reasons.

00:34:46.410 --> 00:34:47.530
It scales well.

00:34:47.570 --> 00:34:48.440
It's very secure.

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:51.440
It was written by a security expert.

00:34:51.440 --> 00:34:53.930
It's easy to configure in terms
of the configuration files.

00:34:53.930 --> 00:34:56.720
If you've ever seen
send mail configuration,

00:34:56.720 --> 00:34:59.000
you know what I'm talking about.

00:34:59.560 --> 00:35:02.020
And then we've all, for IMAP and POP,
we've moved to Cyrus,

00:35:02.020 --> 00:35:03.640
and there were a few
reasons for doing that,

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:03.920
too.

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:05.900
So Cyrus is a proven IMAP server.

00:35:05.900 --> 00:35:10.620
It supports clustering,
so it's easy to scale it.

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:12.480
You can configure it to
work with multiple machines.

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:18.180
And it also supports the ability
to store your mail for different

00:35:18.790 --> 00:35:22.560
accounts on any variety of machines.

00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:26.480
So if you want to segment up your email
users to different back-end stores,

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:28.820
you can do that,
and it's not a problem at all with Cyrus.

00:35:29.500 --> 00:35:32.830
And we are, of course, Kerberizing it,
so it'll work properly

00:35:32.830 --> 00:35:33.680
with single sign-on.

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:38.680
And it also will support,
we will support SSL on our mail servers.

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:42.690
So on top of mailing lists...

00:35:44.460 --> 00:35:48.880
With the mail server we had in the past,
in Jaguar,

00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:53.200
it had a feature that would allow you
to take any group in the directory

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:54.340
and treat that as a mailing list.

00:35:54.340 --> 00:35:56.840
Well, we're losing that because
of the new mail servers,

00:35:56.840 --> 00:35:59.940
but what we've decided to do to kind
of replace that functionality is

00:35:59.940 --> 00:36:01.640
to add a real mailing list server.

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:06.600
So we've added the Mailman
mailing list server.

00:36:06.900 --> 00:36:08.510
Mailman's extremely powerful.

00:36:08.570 --> 00:36:10.980
It's actually the one,
if you go to lists.apple.com,

00:36:10.980 --> 00:36:13.260
it's the one Apple uses for its
mailing lists for the public.

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:17.460
We've built some UI into the
server admin to actually create

00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:19.940
mailing lists in the admin.

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:22.780
Mailman, as you know,
has web-based tools as well,

00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:25.910
so for your end users,
they can go in and they can change

00:36:25.910 --> 00:36:27.840
their options if they want digest mode.

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:29.720
If they don't want digest mode,
they can go to a web page

00:36:29.740 --> 00:36:30.770
and set all of that stuff up.

00:36:31.560 --> 00:36:35.010
It supports all kinds of features,
such as mailed-in-mail-to-news gateways,

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:39.300
bounce handling, spam prevention,
and it's also got email-based

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:43.820
administration commands,
as most good mailing lists do.

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:46.970
Webmail.

00:36:47.060 --> 00:36:51.890
So we have revved the version of webmail
that we're using in Panther Server.

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:56.620
Webmail is a standards-based
webmail package written in PHP.

00:36:56.700 --> 00:36:58.450
There are some really
good things about it.

00:36:58.460 --> 00:36:59.560
One is that it's pure HTML.

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:02.170
It's not using any JavaScript.

00:37:02.340 --> 00:37:05.550
It's compatible with
basically any browser,

00:37:05.580 --> 00:37:07.080
so you don't have to worry
about compatibility there.

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:09.680
Works with any SMTP or IMAP mail server.

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:12.690
I see no reason why you would
need to use it with anything

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:13.740
other than the Panther server.

00:37:13.740 --> 00:37:16.140
Supports MIME encoding.

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:18.700
Address books now, which is new.

00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:19.940
We didn't have that in the prior version.

00:37:19.940 --> 00:37:20.790
Folder manipulation.

00:37:21.440 --> 00:37:24.290
You can host this mail via SSL,
so you can have completely

00:37:24.290 --> 00:37:26.040
secure mail over the web.

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:30.070
And we've gone,
the version that we've moved

00:37:30.070 --> 00:37:32.710
up to now supports Japanese,
so we've got Japanese support

00:37:32.710 --> 00:37:33.380
for Squirrel Mill.

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:37.930
And Eric's going to come up
and demo some mail for you.

00:37:37.940 --> 00:37:41.300
Okay, so we'll go back to
computer number two here.

00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:45.660
And our mail server in the PostMix mail
server is a really great mail server,

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:49.000
so we're really happy to provide a
really good user interface for it.

00:37:49.020 --> 00:37:51.800
So here in the user interface,
the administrator can go in,

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:55.490
they can enable and disable SMTP,
set up their IMAP,

00:37:55.540 --> 00:38:02.260
even have messages sent to
Postmaster at apple.com or whatever.

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:06.760
I can go in and I can
configure the mailing list,

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:08.740
as Chris showed,
in the user interface here.

00:38:08.740 --> 00:38:09.730
You can enable them.

00:38:09.730 --> 00:38:11.360
I can add new ones to it.

00:38:11.420 --> 00:38:12.610
I can set up filters.

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:15.060
Spam prevention is very key,
very important.

00:38:15.060 --> 00:38:18.320
This user interface here allows
us to have a real rich set

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:20.270
of spam filtering options.

00:38:20.280 --> 00:38:23.430
And then also, control many log levels.

00:38:23.440 --> 00:38:28.810
And then the last screen here allows
you to configure the authentication

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:30.420
options in some of the hosts.

00:38:30.440 --> 00:38:34.850
So this is really important if you are
in secure environments or you want to use

00:38:34.890 --> 00:38:36.500
Kerberos only for your authentication.

00:38:36.500 --> 00:38:40.130
Nice feature down here is
the ability to use SSL.

00:38:40.140 --> 00:38:44.440
So I can say, you have to use SSL,
or I can use SSL if it's available,

00:38:44.440 --> 00:38:46.020
or I can require SSL.

00:38:46.020 --> 00:38:48.980
So if you want to implement
secure email on your network,

00:38:48.980 --> 00:38:52.830
you can do that and enforce it in
requirement for all your clients.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:53.970
Great.

00:38:53.970 --> 00:38:56.080
Thanks, Eric.

